<Base title="Hourly to Salary Calculator: Complete US Guide 2025 | SalaryTools" description="How to convert hourly to annual salary. Formulas, overtime, PTO, examples for every pay rate. Plus a free hourly to salary calculator for US workers." page="blog">
<article style="padding-bottom:5rem;">
  <div class="article-hero">
    <div class="container" style="max-width:740px;">
      <div class="article-tag">Guide</div>
      <h1>Hourly to Salary: The Complete US Guide (2025)</h1>
      <div class="article-meta"><span>Jun 18, 2025</span><span>·</span><span>6 min read</span></div>
      <p class="article-intro">Whether you're comparing a job offer, asking for a raise, or just curious — here's everything you need to convert between hourly wages and annual salary in the US.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container" style="max-width:740px;">
    <div class="prose">
      <div class="callout"><strong>Quick formula:</strong> Hourly rate × 40 hours × 52 weeks = Annual salary. Use our <a href="/">free hourly to salary calculator</a> to adjust for overtime, PTO, and custom hours.</div>

      <h2>The basic hourly to annual salary formula</h2>
      <p>The standard formula assumes 40 hours per week and 52 weeks per year:</p>
      <pre><code>Annual salary = Hourly rate × Hours per week × Weeks per year
$25/hr × 40 × 52 = $52,000/year</code></pre>

      <h2>Common hourly rates converted to annual salary</h2>
      <table>
        <tr><th>Hourly Rate</th><th>Annual (40 hrs)</th><th>Monthly</th><th>Biweekly</th></tr>
        <tr><td>$15/hour</td><td>$31,200</td><td>$2,600</td><td>$1,200</td></tr>
        <tr><td>$18/hour</td><td>$37,440</td><td>$3,120</td><td>$1,440</td></tr>
        <tr><td>$20/hour</td><td>$41,600</td><td>$3,467</td><td>$1,600</td></tr>
        <tr><td>$25/hour</td><td>$52,000</td><td>$4,333</td><td>$2,000</td></tr>
        <tr><td>$30/hour</td><td>$62,400</td><td>$5,200</td><td>$2,400</td></tr>
        <tr><td>$40/hour</td><td>$83,200</td><td>$6,933</td><td>$3,200</td></tr>
        <tr><td>$50/hour</td><td>$104,000</td><td>$8,667</td><td>$4,000</td></tr>
        <tr><td>$75/hour</td><td>$156,000</td><td>$13,000</td><td>$6,000</td></tr>
        <tr><td>$100/hour</td><td>$208,000</td><td>$17,333</td><td>$8,000</td></tr>
      </table>

      <h2>How many working hours are in a year?</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>2,080 hours</strong> — standard (40 hrs × 52 weeks)</li>
        <li><strong>2,000 hours</strong> — after 10 federal holidays</li>
        <li><strong>1,960 hours</strong> — after 10 holidays + 1 week PTO</li>
        <li><strong>1,920 hours</strong> — after 10 holidays + 2 weeks PTO</li>
      </ul>
      <p>For take-home pay, PTO doesn't reduce your annual salary since it's paid. Only unpaid days off reduce actual annual earnings.</p>

      <h2>How overtime affects annual salary</h2>
      <p>US federal law (FLSA) requires at least 1.5× pay for hours worked over 40 per week for non-exempt employees. If you work 45 hours per week at $25/hour:</p>
      <pre><code>Regular pay:  40 hrs × $25 × 52 weeks = $52,000
Overtime pay:  5 hrs × $37.50 × 52 weeks = $9,750
Total annual: $61,750</code></pre>

      <h2>Converting annual salary to hourly rate</h2>
      <p>Divide annual salary by total working hours:</p>
      <pre><code>Hourly = Annual salary ÷ (Hours/week × Weeks/year)
$60,000 ÷ (40 × 52) = $28.85/hour</code></pre>

      <h2>Part-time hourly to annual</h2>
      <p>If you work fewer than 40 hours, adjust the formula:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>20 hrs/week: $20/hr × 20 × 52 = <strong>$20,800/year</strong></li>
        <li>30 hrs/week: $20/hr × 30 × 52 = <strong>$31,200/year</strong></li>
        <li>32 hrs/week (4-day week): $20/hr × 32 × 52 = <strong>$33,280/year</strong></li>
      </ul>

      <h2>What is a good hourly wage in the US in 2025?</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Federal minimum:</strong> $7.25/hour (many states are higher)</li>
        <li><strong>Living wage (national avg):</strong> ~$22/hour for a single adult</li>
        <li><strong>Median US wage:</strong> ~$23/hour</li>
        <li><strong>Living wage NYC/SF:</strong> $35–50+/hour</li>
        <li><strong>Middle class:</strong> $25–50/hour ($52K–$104K/year)</li>
      </ul>

